As for LOTR, I haven't read them in a while. I don't have as much time to read as I used to.. (Partly due to EQ) That doesn't stop me from reading a lot of books. Right now I am in the middle of 5 books (The Dragon Bone chair, Path of Daggers, Dragons of Autumn Twilight, Dark Heart, and A Sword for a Dragon. And this isn't including my re-reading the Iron Tower Trilogy and the Myth Series from time to time)<br>
<br>
While I am on the computer I listen to a lot of Audiobooks. (Let's face it.. The EQ music sucks after about 30 seconds)  I have the Lord of the Rings on CD.. It's an incredible audio production done by the BBC. It is 13 hours long and is fully dramatized. There are some omissions from the story, but this is for brevity. I'm guessing they didn't think they could hold a person's attention for longer than 13 episodes.<br>
<br>
An interesting note about the BBC's LotR.. There is an interesting role reversal that takes place in one of the cast. The guy who plays Bilbo in the just released movie (Ian Holm), originally played Frodo in the BBC audio production. I recognized the voice almost immediately, but had to wait for the credits to make sure it was the same guy. More useless trivia for you. =)<br>
